In 2012, as Deputy Prime Minister, Uhuru Kenyatta’s new political vehicle, The National Alliance (TNA) set for official launch, it quietly dropped a key plank in its founding charter: An Integrity code.
The requirements had been designed specifically to lock out disreputable characters, who were eyeing the party ticket for the impending General Election, such as then Nairobi Senator Mike Sonko and former Embakasi MP Ferdinand Waititu.



