That the TNA integrity code was dropped without explanation was not surprising. To its credit, the code denied the likes of Sonko, Waititu and others facing criminal charges or general questions of ethical and moral probity opportunity to vie for elective seats on the party ticket. However, matters of realpolitik forced the party to rethink its lofty ideals. It needed the Sonkos and Waititus of this world to bring out the vote, and to capture the elective seats required to guarantee majorities in key assemblies.
Devolved government
More importantly, the party realised that locking out the likes of Sonko and Waititu on integrity grounds replicating those required Chapter 6 of the Constitution would also disqualify key party leaders, including Mr Kenyatta and his putative presidential election running-mate, United Republican Party (URP) leader William Ruto.



