The integrity requirements were hastily dropped. That is how Kenya ended up with the Jubilee regime of President Kenyatta and Deputy President Ruto, and into the bargain, eventuality, the bonus of Governor Sonko in Nairobi County and Governor Waititu in Kiambu County. The former closed the year last week as the second governor to lose his seat on impeachment. The latter had preceded him into the dust heap with his own ejection from the lofty perch at the beginning of the year.
By finding ways to dance around the integrity requirements of leadership, Jubilee paved the way for the regime, whose spectacular failings have become all too evident even for the brain-dead who so lustily sang the ‘Uhu-Ruto’, ‘Muthamaki’ and ‘Tano Tena’ anthem. It also cursed our gubernatorial mansions with the likes of Sonko, Waititu and others whose leadership failures have seriously undermined the noble goal of devolved government.
A lot of water has passed under the bridge since. The Jubilee Party — formed on the merger of Kenyatta’s TNA and Ruto’s URP — is no more. It exists as a governing party in name only following unofficial divorce of the two key partners, President Kenyatta and his Deputy Ruto. The President has ditched his deputy and teamed up with ODM leader Raila Odinga to drive the Building Bridges Initiative (BBI) that should culminate in a constitutional amendment referendum early next year. Among the key planks of the BBI is the promise to ramp up the war against corruption and also ensure adherence to the leadership integrity code enshrined in both the Constitution and the Laws of Kenya.



